content:
I found the bug on a Tuesday, in production, on a client’s live instance, during their busiest reporting week. A dropdown that filtered a case list was occasionally showing data from the previous filter selection. Not always. Just often enough that three different people had reported it as “the app is being weird” over two weeks before anyone connected the reports to each other.

8 min read
3 hours ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

It took me four hours to find. And when I found it, I didn’t feel relieved. I felt embarrassed, because the bug had been sitting in a useEffect I had written myself, almost a year earlier, and I still didn't fully understand why it was wrong until I saw it fail.
That afternoon is roughly where I’d draw the line between “junior React developer” and whatever I am now. Not because I got smarter overnight, but because it forced me to go back and actually understand the tool I’d been using on autopilot for a year. This is the story of that bug and a handful of others like it, the ones that taught me more than any course did.
Why these mistakes mattered more than they should have
I work at a software house, client-facing, on a platform we’ve built on top of Frappe and ERPNext for food fortification data. The frontend is React, TypeScript, Ant Design. Real users, real deadlines, real consequences when something breaks during a client demo. There’s no sandbox to hide in. When you ship something wrong, someone on a call with the client notices within the hour.
That environment has a way of turning “I’ll clean this up later” into a lie you tell yourself. You don’t get later. You get the next ticket, and the one after that. So the mistakes I made didn’t stay small. They compounded, quietly, until they became the kind of thing that eats a Tuesday.
Mistake one: treating useEffect like a lifecycle method
I came into React from a background that had touched Angular briefly, and I brought the wrong mental model with me. I thought of useEffect as "componentDidMount, but with extra steps." Something ran when the component appeared, something else ran when it disappeared, and the dependency array was just a list of things I should probably put in there so the linter would stop complaining.
That mental model works fine right up until it doesn’t. The dropdown bug I mentioned was a search-as-you-type case discussion filter. Every keystroke fired a fetch. Every fetch eventually resolved and called setState. The problem is that fetches don't resolve in the order they were sent. Someone types "case A", then quickly changes their mind and types "case B". If the request for "A" happens to take longer to resolve than the request for "B", the "A" response lands last and overwrites the correct "B" results on screen.
My first fix was embarrassing. I added a debounce. It helped, but it didn’t fix the actual problem, it just made it less likely, which in a QA environment looks like “fixed” and in production three weeks later looks like “still broken, just rarer.”
The real fix was an ignore flag inside the effect’s cleanup function:
useEffect(() => {
let ignore = false; async function fetchResults() {
const data = await searchCases(query);
if (!ignore) {
setResults(data);
}
} fetchResults(); return () => {
ignore = true;
};
}, [query]);What changed for me wasn’t the code, it was the framing. I stopped thinking of the effect as “do this thing when the component mounts” and started thinking of it as “keep this external thing synchronized with these values.” Every time query changes, the old synchronization is stale and needs to be told so. The cleanup function isn't a goodbye party for the component, it's how you tell the outside world that the thing it was syncing to has moved on.
That reframe is the single most useful shift I’ve had in three years of writing React. Once effects are about synchronization instead of lifecycle, the dependency array stops being a puzzle you fight with the linter over. It just becomes an honest list of what the effect depends on.
Worth adding: the ignore flag stops stale data from landing in state, but the network request is still running underneath. If you’re on fetch, wiring in an AbortController cancels the actual call too, which matters more than it sounds like it does when someone is typing fast and leaving five dead requests trailing behind the sixth.
Mistake two: reaching for useEffect when I didn’t need one at all
Once I understood effects properly, I swung too far the other way and started seeing synchronization problems everywhere, including places where there wasn’t an external system to sync with at all.
I had a component that computed a derived total from a list of line items. Something like an invoice total, or a case count grouped by status, I don’t remember exactly which project this was for anymore. What I do remember is the code:
const [items, setItems] = useState(initialItems);
const [total, setTotal] = useState(0);useEffect(() => {
setTotal(items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.amount, 0));
}, [items]);This worked. It also meant every update to items triggered a re-render, which then triggered an effect, which then triggered a second re-render to reflect the new total. Two renders for what should have been one. On a small list nobody notices. On a case list with a few hundred rows and a handful of these derived fields, the app felt sluggish in a way I couldn't explain until I opened the React DevTools profiler and watched the double-render happen in real time.
The fix was almost insulting in how simple it was:
const total = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.amount, 0);No state, no effect, no second render. If you can calculate a value during render from things you already have, you don’t need an effect for it. I’d read this advice before I made the mistake. Reading it and internalizing it turned out to be very different things. I needed to see the extra render in the profiler with my own eyes before it actually stuck.
The pattern I try to hold onto now: effects are for synchronizing with something outside React, a network request, a subscription, the DOM, browser storage. If the entire computation happens using values you already have in scope, it belongs in the render itself, or in a useMemo if it's expensive enough to be worth caching.
Mistake three: not understanding what actually causes a re-render
For a long time I treated re-renders as something that just happened to me, like weather. Something felt slow, I’d wrap it in React.memo, and if that didn't help I'd shrug and move on. I wasn't diagnosing anything. I was pattern-matching against a checklist.
The moment that changed was a form component we called DynamicForm, which rendered fields based on a doctype definition coming from the backend. It had grown over several months into something with real cognitive complexity, the kind SonarQube flags in red and nobody wants to touch. Every keystroke in any single field was causing the entire form to re-render, all thirty-plus fields, even the ones with no relationship to what was being typed.
I assumed this was a memoization problem and spent a day wrapping individual field components in React.memo. It barely helped. The actual issue was that the parent component held all field values in a single state object, and every keystroke replaced that object with a new reference, which meant every child that read from it saw a new prop and had every reason to re-render regardless of memoization, because the object itself was new even if most of its contents weren't.
javascript
// Every keystroke replaces the whole object
const [formValues, setFormValues] = useState({});const handleChange = (field, value) => {
setFormValues(prev => ({ ...prev, [field]: value }));
};React.memo compares props by reference by default. A new object reference on every keystroke defeats it completely, no matter how many components you wrap. What actually helped was splitting form state so each field managed its own value and only lifted state up on blur or submit, combined with a registry pattern for field rendering so we weren't recomputing the entire field list on every value change. It's more code. It's also the difference between a form that feels responsive and one that has a visible half-second lag on a mid-range laptop.
The lesson wasn’t “use memo more.” It was that memoization only solves a re-render problem if the re-render is actually caused by unnecessary prop identity changes. If your state shape itself is forcing new references everywhere, no amount of memoization fixes that, you’re treating a symptom with the wrong medicine.
The tradeoffs nobody tells you about upfront
None of these fixes are free. The ignore flag pattern adds a bit of ceremony to every data-fetching effect, and if you’re doing it in ten different components you’ll eventually want to extract it into a custom hook, which is its own decision with its own tradeoffs around abstraction versus readability. Splitting form state per field means more components, more files, more places to look when something goes wrong, in exchange for performance that actually matters at scale.
There’s also a real cost to caring about this stuff too early. I’ve seen developers, myself included on a bad day, spend an hour micro-optimizing a component that renders twice a session and would never have been noticeable to a single user. Performance work has to be justified by an actual symptom, a slow interaction someone complained about, a profiler flame graph that points somewhere specific. Otherwise, you’re just adding complexity as a hobby and calling it engineering discipline.
The honest answer is that React gives you a lot of rope, and it doesn’t tell you when you’re about to hang yourself with it. useEffect will run whatever you put in it whether or not it makes sense as a synchronization boundary. React.memo will silently do nothing useful if your props are shaped wrong. The framework is not going to stop you from writing code that works in development and falls apart under real usage patterns. That part is on you, and it only gets easier with reps.
What actually changed in how I think
Three years in, the biggest shift isn’t that I know more hooks or more patterns. It’s that I stopped asking “how do I make this work” as the first question and started asking “what is this code actually depending on, and what happens when that dependency changes.” That question applies to effects, to memoization, to state shape, to almost everything that used to trip me up.
I still get things wrong. Last month I shipped a stale closure bug in an interval that I didn’t catch until QA flagged it, so this isn’t a story about arriving somewhere and being done. It’s more that the mistakes got smaller and slower to repeat, and when they do happen, I recognize the shape of them faster, because I’ve usually seen some version of that shape before.
If there’s one thing I’d tell the version of myself who wrote that dropdown bug, it’s that reading about a concept and being burned by it in production teach you two completely different things, and there’s no shortcut from the first to the second. You just have to ship the bug, feel bad about it for an afternoon, and actually go find out why.
